US journalist Jill Carroll, working for the Christian Science Monitor, was kidnapped in Iraq.
Her Iraqi interpreter was killed during the abduction.
Carroll, the 31st media worker kidnapped in Iraq since 2003, was seized in Baghdad.
The US government denied negotiating with insurgents but acknowledged reaching out to those rejecting the political process.
A study co-authored by a Nobel Prize economist estimated the Iraq war could cost the US up to two trillion dollars.
Carroll's family issued an emotional plea for her release after her captors threatened her with execution.
The Islamic Army of Iraq claimed to have killed another hostage, Ronald Schulz.
